# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: raygui
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics are mainly used in applications that were originally developed upon traditional printing and drawing technologies, such as typography, cartography, technical drawing, advertising, etc.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] In many domains, such as desktop publishing, engineering, and business, a description of a document based on 2D computer graphics techniques can be much smaller than the corresponding digital image—often by a factor of 1/1000 or more.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] This representation is also more flexible since it can be rendered at different resolutions to suit different output devices.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, documents and illustrations are often stored or transmitted as 2D graphic files.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics started in the 1950s, based on vector graphics devices.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] These were largely supplanted by raster-based devices in the following decades.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] The PostScript language and the X Window System protocol were landmark developments in the field.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics models may combine geometric models (also called vector graphics), digital images (also called raster graphics), text to be typeset (defined by content, font style and size, color, position, and orientation), mathematical functions and equations, and more.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] These components can be modified and manipulated by two-dimensional geometric transformations such as translation, rotation, and scaling.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] In object-oriented graphics, the image is described indirectly by an object endowed with a self-rendering method—a procedure that assigns colors to the image pixels by an arbitrary algorithm.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Complex models can be built by combining simpler objects, in the paradigms of object-oriented programming.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] In Euclidean geometry, a *translation (geometry)* moves every point a constant distance in a specified direction.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can be described as a rigid motion: other rigid motions include rotations and reflections.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can also be interpreted as the addition of a constant vector to every point, or as shifting the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] If *T* is a translation, then the image of a subset *A* under the function *T* is the **translation** of *A* by *T*.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] The translation of *A* by *T***v** is often written *A* + **v**.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] In a Euclidean space, any translation is an isometry.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all translations forms the translation group *T*, which is isomorphic to the space itself, and a normal subgroup of Euclidean group *E*(*n* ).
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Since a translation is an affine transformation but not a linear transformation, homogeneous coordinates are normally used to represent the translation operator by a matrix and thus to make it linear.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Because addition of vectors is commutative, multiplication of translation matrices is therefore also commutative (unlike multiplication of arbitrary matrices).
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] In linear algebra, a *rotation matrix* is a matrix that is used to perform a rotation in Euclidean space.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] rotates points in the *xy*-Cartesian plane counterclockwise through an angle *θ* about the origin of the Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] To perform the rotation using a rotation matrix *R*, the position of each point must be represented by a column vector **v**, containing the coordinates of the point.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] A rotated vector is obtained by using the matrix multiplication *R***v**.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Since matrix multiplication has no effect on the zero vector (i.e., on the coordinates of the origin), rotation matrices can only be used to describe rotations about the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices provide a simple algebraic description of such rotations, and are used extensively for computations in geometry, physics, and computer graphics.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] In 2-dimensional space, a rotation can be simply described by an angle *θ* of rotation, but it can be also represented by the 4 entries of a rotation matrix with 2 rows and 2 columns.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] In 3-dimensional space, every rotation can be interpreted as a rotation by a given angle about a single fixed axis of rotation (see Euler's rotation theorem), and hence it can be simply described by an angle and a vector with 3 entries.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] However, it can also be represented by the 9 entries of a rotation matrix with 3 rows and 3 columns.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] The notion of rotation is not commonly used in dimensions higher than 3; there is a notion of a *rotational displacement*, which can be represented by a matrix, but no associated single axis or angle.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices are square matrices, with real entries.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all such matrices of size *n* forms a group, known as the special orthogonal group SO(*n*).
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] A convenient way to create a complex image is to start with a blank "canvas" raster map (an array of pixels, also known as a bitmap) filled with some uniform background color and then "draw", "paint" or "paste" simple patches of color onto it, in an appropriate order.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] In particular the canvas may be the frame buffer for a computer display.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Text, shapes and lines are rendered with a client-specified color.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Many libraries and cards provide color gradients, which are handy for the generation of smoothly-varying backgrounds, shadow effects, etc.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] The pixel colors can also be taken from a texture, e.g. a digital image (thus emulating rub-on screentones and the fabled *checker paint* which used to be available only in cartoons).
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Painting a pixel with a given color usually replaces its previous color.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] However, many systems support painting with transparent and translucent colors, which only modify the previous pixel values.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] The two colors may also be combined in more complex ways, e.g. by computing their bitwise exclusive or.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] This technique is known as *inverting color* or *color inversion*, and is often used in graphical user interfaces for highlighting, rubber-band drawing, and other volatile painting—since re-painting the same shapes with the same color will restore the original pixel values.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] The models used in 2D computer graphics usually do not provide for three-dimensional shapes, or three-dimensional optical phenomena such as lighting, shadows, reflection, refraction, etc.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] However, they usually can model multiple *layers* (conceptually of ink, paper, or film; opaque, translucent, or transparent—stacked in a specific order.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] The ordering is usually defined by a single number (the layer's *depth*, or distance from the viewer).
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are sometimes called "21⁄2-D computer graphics".
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] They make it possible to mimic traditional drafting and printing techniques based on film and paper, such as cutting and pasting; and allow the user to edit any layer without affecting the others.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, they are used in most graphics editors.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models also allow better spatial anti-aliasing of complex drawings and provide a sound model for certain techniques such as *mitered joints* and the even–odd rule.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are also used to allow the user to suppress unwanted information when viewing or printing a document, e.g. roads or railways from a map, certain process layers from an integrated circuit diagram, or hand annotations from a business letter.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] In a layer-based model, the target image is produced by "painting" or "pasting" each layer, in order of decreasing depth, on the virtual canvas.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Conceptually, each layer is first rendered on its own, yielding a digital image with the desired resolution which is then painted over the canvas, pixel by pixel.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Fully transparent parts of a layer need not be rendered, of course.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] The rendering and painting may be done in parallel, i.e., each layer pixel may be painted on the canvas as soon as it is produced by the rendering procedure.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Layers that consist of complex geometric objects (such as text or polylines) may be broken down into simpler elements (characters or line segments, respectively), which are then painted as separate layers, in some order.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] However, this solution may create undesirable aliasing artifacts wherever two elements overlap the same pixel.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] See also Portable Document Format#Layers.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Modern computer graphics card displays almost overwhelmingly use raster techniques, dividing the screen into a rectangular grid of pixels, due to the relatively low cost of raster-based video hardware as compared with vector graphic hardware.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Most graphic hardware has internal support for blitting operations or sprite drawing.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] A co-processor dedicated to blitting is known as a *Blitter chip*.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Many graphical user interfaces (GUIs), including macOS, Microsoft Windows, or the X Window System, are primarily based on 2D graphical concepts.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Such software provides a visual environment for interacting with the computer, and commonly includes some form of window manager to aid the user in conceptually distinguishing between different applications.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] The user interface within individual software applications is typically 2D in nature as well, due in part to the fact that most common input devices, such as the mouse, are constrained to two dimensions of movement.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics are very important in the control peripherals such as printers, plotters, sheet cutting machines, etc.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] They were also used in most early video games; and are still used for card and board games such as solitaire, chess, mahjongg, etc.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics editors or *drawing programs* are application-level software for the creation of images, diagrams and illustrations by direct manipulation (through the mouse, graphics tablet, or similar device) of 2D computer graphics primitives.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally provide geometric primitives as well as digital images; and some even support procedural models.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] The illustration is usually represented internally as a layered model, often with a hierarchical structure to make editing more convenient.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally output graphics files where the layers and primitives are separately preserved in their original form.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] MacDraw, introduced in 1984 with the Macintosh line of computers, was an early example of this class; recent examples are the commercial products Adobe Illustrator and CorelDRAW, and the free editors such as xfig or Inkscape.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] There are also many 2D graphics editors specialized for certain types of drawings such as electrical, electronic and VLSI diagrams, topographic maps, computer fonts, etc.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Image editors are specialized for the manipulation of digital images, mainly by means of free-hand drawing/painting and signal processing operations.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] They typically use a direct-painting paradigm, where the user controls virtual pens, brushes, and other free-hand artistic instruments to apply paint to a virtual canvas.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Some image editors support a multiple-layer model; however, in order to support signal-processing operations like blurring each layer is normally represented as a digital image.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Therefore, any geometric primitives that are provided by the editor are immediately converted to pixels and painted onto the canvas.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] The name *raster graphics editor* is sometimes used to contrast this approach to that of general editors which also handle *vector graphics*.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] One of the first popular image editors was Apple's MacPaint, companion to MacDraw.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Modern examples are the free GIMP editor, and the commercial products Photoshop and Paint Shop Pro.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] This class too includes many specialized editors—for medicine, remote sensing, digital photography, etc.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] With the resurgence of 2D animation, free and proprietary software packages have become widely available for amateurs and professional animators.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] With software like RETAS UbiArt Framework and Adobe After Effects, coloring and compositing can be done in less time.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Various approaches have been developed to aid and speed up the process of digital 2D animation.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] For example, by generating vector artwork in a tool like Adobe Flash an artist may employ software-driven automatic coloring and in-betweening.
[src:raygui/2d-computer-graphics] Programs like Blender or Adobe Substance allow the user to do either 3D animation, 2D animation or combine both in its software allowing experimentation with multiple forms of animation.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] A **graphics library** or **graphics API** is a program library designed to aid in rendering computer graphics to a monitor.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] This typically involves providing optimized versions of functions that handle common rendering tasks.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] This can be done purely in software and running on the CPU, common in embedded systems, or being hardware accelerated by a GPU, more common in PCs.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] By employing these functions, a program can assemble an image to be output to a monitor.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] This relieves the programmer of the task of creating and optimizing these functions, and allows them to focus on building the graphics program.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] Graphics libraries are mainly used in video games and simulations.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] The use of graphics libraries in connection with video production systems, such as Pixar RenderMan, is not covered here.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] Some APIs use Graphics Library (GL) in their name, notably OpenGL and WebGL.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] Dedicated graphics processors use RAM allocated directly to the graphics processor rather than the computer’s main system memory.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] This RAM is usually specifically selected with the expected sequential load of the graphics card in mind (see GDDR).
[src:raygui/graphics-library] Sometimes systems with dedicated discrete graphics processors were called “DIS” systems in contrast to “UMA” systems.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] Technologies such as 3dfx's Scan-Line Interleave, Nvidia's SLI and NVLink, and AMD's CrossFire allow multiple graphics processors to simultaneously display images on one screen, increasing the computational power available for graphics processing.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] However, these technologies are becoming increasingly rare; most games do not utilize all the capabilities of multiple graphics processors since most users cannot afford them.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] Today, laptops and mini-PCs require powerful integrated graphics.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] In many cases, quality integrated graphics can replace a discrete graphics card, enhancing laptop portability and mini-PC compactness while maintaining performance.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] Integrated graphics processors (IGPU), integrated graphics, shared graphics solutions, integrated graphics processors (IGP), or unified memory architectures (UMA) use part of the computer’s RAM rather than dedicated graphics memory.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] IGP may be integrated into the motherboard as part of its northbridge chipset or on a single chip (integrated circuit) with the central processor (e.g., AMD APU or Intel HD Graphics).
[src:raygui/graphics-library] On some motherboards, AMD’s IGP may use sideport dedicated memory: a separate fixed block of high-performance memory allocated for use by the graphics processor.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] As of early 2007, computers with integrated graphics accounted for about 90% of all PC shipments.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] They are less expensive to implement than dedicated graphics processing but generally less powerful.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] Historically, integrated processing was considered unsuitable for 3D games or graphics-intensive applications but could run less resource-demanding programs like Adobe Flash.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] Examples of such IGPs include offerings from SiS and VIA around 2004.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] However, modern integrated graphics processors such as AMD Accelerated Processing Unit and Intel Graphics Technology (HD, UHD, Iris, Iris Pro, Iris Plus, and Xe-LP) can handle 2D graphics or undemanding 3D graphics.
[src:raygui/graphics-library] In systems with a “unified memory architecture” (UMA), including modern AMD processors with integrated graphics, modern Intel processors with integrated graphics, Apple processors, PS5, and Xbox Series (among others), the CPU cores and GPU unit share the same pool of RAM and memory address space.
[src:raygui/immediate-mode-gui] without the use of extensive indirection – thus***immediate***– to retained resources.
[src:raygui/immediate-mode-gui] It does not preclude the use of double-buffering.
[src:raygui/immediate-mode-gui] Retained mode is an alternative approach.
[src:raygui/immediate-mode-gui] Historically, retained mode has been the dominant style in GUI libraries; however, both can coexist in the same library and are not necessarily exclusive in practice.
[src:raygui/immediate-mode-gui] In immediate mode, the scene (complete object model of the rendering primitives) is retained in the memory space of the client, instead of the graphics library.
[src:raygui/immediate-mode-gui] This implies that in an immediate mode application, the lists of graphical objects to be rendered are kept by the client and are not saved by the graphics library API.
[src:raygui/immediate-mode-gui] The application must re-issue all drawing commands required to describe the entire scene each time a new frame is required, regardless of actual changes.
[src:raygui/immediate-mode-gui] This method provides on the one hand a maximum of control and flexibility to the application program, but on the other hand it also generates continuous work load on the CPU.
[src:raygui/immediate-mode-gui] Examples of immediate mode rendering systems include Direct2D, OpenGL and Quartz.
[src:raygui/immediate-mode-gui] There are some immediate mode GUIs that are particularly suitable when used in conjunction with immediate mode rendering systems.
[src:raygui/immediate-mode-gui] Primitive vertex attribute data may be inserted frame by frame into a command buffer by a rendering API.
[src:raygui/immediate-mode-gui] This involves significant bandwidth and processor time (especially if the graphics processing unit is on a separate bus), but may be advantageous for data generated dynamically by the CPU.
[src:raygui/immediate-mode-gui] It is less common since the advent of increasingly versatile shaders, with which a graphics processing unit may generate increasingly complex effects without the need for CPU intervention.
[src:raygui/immediate-mode-gui] Graphical user interfaces traditionally use retained mode-style API design, but immediate mode GUIs instead use an immediate mode-style API design, in which user code directly specifies the GUI elements to draw in the user input loop.
[src:raygui/immediate-mode-gui] For example, rather than having a CreateButton() function that a user would call once to instantiate a button, an immediate-mode GUI API may have a DoButton() function which should be called whenever the button should be on screen.
[src:raygui/immediate-mode-gui] The technique was developed by Casey Muratori in 2002.
[src:raygui/immediate-mode-gui] Prominent implementations include Omar Cornut's Dear ImGui in C++, Nic Barker's Clay in C and Micha Mettke's Nuklear in C.
[src:raygui/opengl] (SGI) began developing OpenGL in 1991 and released it on June 30, 1992.
[src:raygui/opengl] It is used for a variety of applications, including computer-aided design (CAD), video games, scientific visualization, virtual reality, and flight simulation.
[src:raygui/opengl] Since 2006, OpenGL has been managed by the non-profit technology consortium Khronos Group.
[src:raygui/opengl] The OpenGL specification describes an abstract application programming interface (API) for drawing 2D and 3D graphics.
[src:raygui/opengl] It is designed to be implemented mostly or entirely using hardware acceleration such as a GPU, although it is possible for the API to be implemented entirely in software running on a CPU.
[src:raygui/opengl] The API is defined as a set of functions which may be called by the client program, alongside a set of named integer constants (for example, the constant GL_TEXTURE_2D, which corresponds to the decimal number 3553).
[src:raygui/opengl] Although the function definitions are superficially similar to those of the programming language C, they are language-independent.
[src:raygui/opengl] As such, OpenGL has many language bindings, some of the most noteworthy being the JavaScript binding WebGL (API, based on OpenGL ES 2.0, for 3D rendering from within a web browser); the C bindings WGL, GLX and CGL; the C binding provided by iOS; and the Java and C bindings provided by Android.
[src:raygui/opengl] In addition to being language-independent, OpenGL is also cross-platform.
[src:raygui/opengl] The specification says nothing on the subject of obtaining and managing an OpenGL context, leaving this as a detail of the underlying windowing system.
[src:raygui/opengl] For the same reason, OpenGL is purely concerned with rendering, providing no APIs related to input, audio, or windowing.
[src:raygui/opengl] New versions of the OpenGL specifications are released by the Khronos Group, each of which extends the API to support various new features.
[src:raygui/opengl] The details of each version are decided by consensus between the Group's members, including graphics card manufacturers, operating system designers, and general technology companies such as Mozilla and Google.
[src:raygui/opengl] In addition to the features required by the core API, graphics processing unit (GPU) vendors may provide additional functionality in the form of *extensions*.
[src:raygui/opengl] Extensions may introduce new functions and new constants, and may relax or remove restrictions on existing OpenGL functions.
[src:raygui/opengl] Vendors can use extensions to expose custom APIs without needing support from other vendors or the Khronos Group as a whole, which greatly increases the flexibility of OpenGL.
[src:raygui/opengl] All extensions are collected in, and defined by, the OpenGL Registry.
[src:raygui/opengl] The features introduced by each new version of OpenGL are typically formed from the combined features of several widely implemented extensions, especially extensions of type ARB or EXT.
[src:raygui/opengl] OpenGL is no longer in active development; whereas between 2001 and 2014, OpenGL specification was updated mostly on a yearly basis, with two releases (3.1 and 3.2) taking place in 2009 and three (3.3, 4.0 and 4.1) in 2010.
[src:raygui/opengl] The latest OpenGL specification 4.6 was released in 2017 after a three-year break, and was limited to inclusion of eleven existing ARB and EXT extensions into the core profile.
[src:raygui/opengl] Active development of OpenGL was dropped in favor of the Vulkan API, released in 2016, and codenamed glNext during initial development.
[src:raygui/opengl] In 2017, Khronos Group announced that OpenGL ES would not have new versions and has since concentrated on development of Vulkan and other technologies.
[src:raygui/opengl] As a result, certain capabilities offered by modern GPUs, e.g. ray tracing, are not supported by the OpenGL standard.
[src:raygui/opengl] However, support for newer features might be provided through the vendor-specific OpenGL extensions.
[src:raygui/opengl] The OpenGL Architecture Review Board released a series of manuals along with the specification which have been updated to track changes in the API.
[src:raygui/opengl] OpenGL Programming for the X Window System.
[src:raygui/opengl] Includes a poster-sized fold-out diagram showing the structure of an idealised OpenGL implementation.
[src:raygui/opengl] OpenGL Programming for Windows 95 and Windows NT.
[src:raygui/opengl] A book about interfacing OpenGL with Microsoft Windows.
[src:raygui/opengl] OpenGL's documentation is also accessible via its official webpage.
[src:raygui/opengl] The earliest versions of OpenGL were released with a companion library called the OpenGL Utility Library (GLU).
[src:raygui/opengl] It provided simple, useful features which were unlikely to be supported in contemporary hardware, such as tessellating, and generating mipmaps and primitive shapes.
[src:raygui/opengl] The GLU specification was last updated in 1998 and depends on OpenGL features which are now deprecated.
[src:raygui/opengl] Given that creating an OpenGL context is quite a complex process, and given that it varies between operating systems, automatic OpenGL context creation has become a common feature of several game-development and user-interface libraries, including SDL, Allegro, SFML, FLTK, and Qt.
[src:raygui/opengl] A few libraries have been designed solely to produce an OpenGL-capable window.
[src:raygui/opengl] The first such library was OpenGL Utility Toolkit (GLUT), later superseded by freeglut.
[src:raygui/opengl] Given the high workload involved in identifying and loading OpenGL extensions, a few libraries have been designed which load all available extensions and functions automatically.
[src:raygui/opengl] Examples include OpenGL Easy Extension library (GLEE), OpenGL Extension Wrangler Library (GLEW) and glbinding.
[src:raygui/opengl] Extensions are also loaded automatically by most language bindings, such as Java OpenGL, PyOpenGL and WebGL.
[src:raygui/opengl] Mesa 3D is an open-source implementation of OpenGL.
[src:raygui/opengl] It can do pure software rendering, and it may also use hardware acceleration on BSD, Linux, and other platforms by taking advantage of the Direct Rendering Infrastructure.
[src:raygui/opengl] As of version 20.0, it implements version 4.6 of the OpenGL standard.
[src:raygui/opengl] In the 1980s, developing software that could function with a wide range of graphics hardware was a challenge without a cross-platform library.
[src:raygui/opengl] Software developers wrote custom interfaces and drivers for each piece of hardware.
[src:raygui/opengl] This was expensive and resulted in multiplication of effort.
[src:raygui/opengl] By the early 1990s, Silicon Graphics (SGI) was a leader in 3D graphics for workstations.
[src:raygui/opengl] Their IRIS GL API became the industry standard, as IRIS GL was considered easier to use, and it supported immediate mode rendering, therefore being faster than competitors like PHIGS.
[src:raygui/opengl] SGI's competitors (including Sun Microsystems, Hewlett-Packard and IBM) were also able to bring to market 3D hardware supported by extensions made to the PHIGS standard, which pressured SGI to open source a version of IRIS GL as a public standard called **OpenGL**.
[src:raygui/opengl] However, SGI had many customers for whom the change from IRIS GL to OpenGL would demand significant investment.
[src:raygui/opengl] Moreover, IRIS GL had API functions that were irrelevant to 3D graphics.
[src:raygui/opengl] For example, it included a windowing, keyboard and mouse API, in part because it was developed before the X Window System and Sun's NeWS.
[src:raygui/opengl] IRIS GL libraries were heavily tied into SGI's proprietary graphics hardware and could not be open sourced as-is due to hardware patents and trade secrets.
[src:raygui/opengl] These factors required SGI to continue to support the advanced and proprietary Iris Inventor and Iris Performer programming APIs while market support for OpenGL matured.
[src:raygui/opengl] One of the restrictions of IRIS GL was that it only provided access to features supported by the underlying hardware.
[src:raygui/opengl] If the graphics hardware did not support a feature natively, then the application could not use it.
[src:raygui/opengl] OpenGL overcame this problem by providing software implementations of features unsupported by hardware, allowing applications to use advanced graphics on relatively low-powered systems.
[src:raygui/opengl] OpenGL standardized access to hardware, pushed the development responsibility of hardware interface programs (device drivers) to hardware manufacturers, and delegated windowing functions to the underlying operating system.
[src:raygui/opengl] With so many different kinds of graphics hardware, getting them all to speak the same language in this way had a remarkable impact by giving software developers a higher-level platform for 3D-software development.
[src:raygui/opengl] In 1992, SGI led the creation of the OpenGL Architecture Review Board (OpenGL ARB), the group of companies that would maintain and expand the OpenGL specification in the future.
[src:raygui/opengl] Two years later, they also played with the idea of releasing something called "OpenGL++" which included elements such as a scene-graph API (presumably based on their Performer technology).
[src:raygui/opengl] The specification was circulated among a few interested parties – but never turned into a product.
[src:raygui/opengl] Released in 1996, Microsoft's Direct3D eventually became the main competitor of OpenGL.
[src:raygui/opengl] Over 50 game developers signed an open letter to Microsoft, released on June 12, 1997, calling on the company to actively support OpenGL.
[src:raygui/opengl] On December 17, 1997, Microsoft and SGI initiated the Fahrenheit project, which was a joint effort with the goal of unifying the OpenGL and Direct3D interfaces (and adding a scene-graph API too).
[src:raygui/opengl] In 1998, Hewlett-Packard joined the project.
[src:raygui/opengl] It initially showed some promise of bringing order to the world of interactive 3D computer graphics APIs, but on account of financial constraints at SGI, strategic reasons at Microsoft, and a general lack of industry support, it was abandoned in 1999.
[src:raygui/opengl] In July 2006, the OpenGL Architecture Review Board voted to transfer control of the OpenGL API standard to the Khronos Group.
[src:raygui/opengl] OpenGL was the standard for many CAD software (such as Blender) and games in the 1990s and 2000s, and faces wide support across virtually all hardware vendors.
[src:raygui/opengl] Despite the emergence of newer graphics APIs like its successor Vulkan or Metal, OpenGL continues to be a widely used standard.
[src:raygui/opengl] This continued relevance is supported by several factors: ongoing development with new extensions and driver optimizations, its cross-platform compatibility, and the availability of compatibility layers like ANGLE and Zink.
[src:raygui/opengl] These layers allow OpenGL to run efficiently on top of Vulkan and Metal, offering a pathway for continued use or gradual transitions for developers.
[src:raygui/opengl] However, the graphics API landscape has been shifting, where some companies are moving away from OpenGL.
[src:raygui/opengl] In June 2018, Apple deprecated OpenGL APIs on all of their platforms (iOS, macOS and tvOS), encouraging developers to use their proprietary Metal API, which was introduced in 2014.
[src:raygui/opengl] Game developers have also begun to adopt newer APIs. id Software, who has been using OpenGL in their games since the late 1990s in games such as GLQuake or some games of the Doom franchise, transitioned away to its successor Vulkan in its id Tech 7 engine in 2016.
[src:raygui/opengl] They first supported Vulkan in an update for their id Tech 6 engine.
[src:raygui/opengl] The company's first licensed use of OpenGL was in its Quake II engine, also known as id Tech 2.
[src:raygui/opengl] In March 2023, Valve removed OpenGL support from Dota 2 in favor of Vulkan.
[src:raygui/opengl] Atypical Games, with support from Samsung, updated their game engine to use Vulkan, rather than OpenGL, across all non-Apple platforms.
[src:raygui/opengl] The Khronos Group, the consortium responsible for OpenGL's development, has stopped updating OpenGL, with the last release made in 2017.
[src:raygui/opengl] It has not received a number of modern graphics technologies, such as hardware accelerated Ray Tracing, on-GPU video decoding, and advanced anti-aliasing algorithms like Nvidia DLSS and AMD FSR.
[src:raygui/opengl] Another modern feature, Mesh Shaders, was initially only supported through an Nvidia exclusive extension, however in 2025, a cross-vendor OpenGL Mesh Shader extension was released.
[src:raygui/opengl] Google's Fuchsia OS, while using Vulkan natively and requiring a Vulkan-conformant GPU, still intends to support OpenGL on top of Vulkan via the ANGLE translation layer.
[src:raygui/opengl] The first version of OpenGL, version 1.0, was released on June 30, 1992, by Mark Segal and Kurt Akeley.
[src:raygui/opengl] Since then, OpenGL has occasionally been extended by releasing a new version of the specification.
[src:raygui/opengl] Such releases define a baseline set of features which all conforming graphics cards must support, and against which new extensions can more easily be written.
[src:raygui/opengl] Each new version of OpenGL tends to incorporate several extensions which have widespread support among graphics-card vendors, although the details of those extensions may be changed.
[src:raygui/opengl] OpenGL 2.0 was originally conceived by 3Dlabs to address concerns that OpenGL was stagnating and lacked a strong direction.
[src:raygui/opengl] 3Dlabs proposed a number of major additions to the standard.
[src:raygui/opengl] Most of these were, at the time, rejected by the ARB or otherwise never came to fruition in the form that 3Dlabs proposed.
[src:raygui/opengl] However, their proposal for a C-style shading language was eventually completed, resulting in the current formulation of the OpenGL Shading Language (GLSL or GLslang).
[src:raygui/opengl] Like the assembly-like shading languages it was replacing, it allowed replacing the fixed-function vertex and fragment pipe with shaders, though this time written in a C-like high-level language.
[src:raygui/opengl] The design of GLSL was notable for making relatively few concessions to the limits of the hardware then available.
[src:raygui/opengl] This harked back to the earlier tradition of OpenGL setting an ambitious, forward-looking target for 3D accelerators rather than merely tracking the state of currently available hardware.
[src:raygui/opengl] The final OpenGL 2.0 specification includes support for GLSL 1.10.
[src:raygui/opengl] OpenGL 2.1 adds support for Pixel Buffer Objects, sRGB textures and GLSL 1.20.
[src:raygui/opengl] Before the release of OpenGL 3.0, the new revision had the codename Longs Peak.
[src:raygui/opengl] At the time of its original announcement, Longs Peak was presented as the first major API revision in OpenGL's lifetime.
[src:raygui/opengl] It consisted of an overhaul to the way that OpenGL works, calling for fundamental changes to the API.
[src:raygui/opengl] The draft introduced a change to object management.
[src:raygui/opengl] The GL 2.1 object model was built upon the state-based design of OpenGL.
[src:raygui/opengl] That is, to modify an object or to use it, one needs to bind the object to the state system, then make modifications to the state or perform function calls that use the bound object.
[src:raygui/opengl] Because of OpenGL's use of a state system, objects must be mutable.
[src:raygui/opengl] That is, the basic structure of an object can change at any time, even if the rendering pipeline is asynchronously using that object.
[src:raygui/opengl] A texture object can be redefined from 2D to 3D.
[src:raygui/opengl] This requires any OpenGL implementations to add a degree of complexity to internal object management.
[src:raygui/opengl] Under the Longs Peak API, object creation would become atomic, using templates to define the properties of an object which would be created with one function call.
[src:raygui/opengl] The object could then be used immediately across multiple threads.
[src:raygui/opengl] Objects would also be immutable; however, they could have their contents changed and updated.
[src:raygui/opengl] For example, a texture could change its image, but its size and format could not be changed.
[src:raygui/opengl] To support backwards compatibility, the old state based API would still be available, but no new functionality would be exposed via the old API in later versions of OpenGL.
[src:raygui/opengl] This would have allowed legacy code bases, such as the majority of CAD products, to continue to run while other software could be written against or ported to the new API.
[src:raygui/opengl] Longs Peak was initially due to be finalized in September 2007 under the name OpenGL 3.0, but the Khronos Group announced on October 30 that it had run into several issues that it wished to address before releasing the specification.
[src:raygui/opengl] As a result, the spec was delayed, and the Khronos Group went into a media blackout until the release of the final OpenGL 3.0 spec.
[src:raygui/opengl] The final specification proved far less revolutionary than the Longs Peak proposal.
[src:raygui/opengl] Instead of removing all immediate mode and fixed functionality (non-shader mode), the spec included them as deprecated features.
[src:raygui/opengl] The proposed object model was not included, and no plans have been announced to include it in any future revisions.
[src:raygui/opengl] As a result, the API remained largely the same with a few existing extensions being promoted to core functionality.
[src:raygui/opengl] Among some developer groups this decision caused something of an uproar, with many developers professing that they would switch to DirectX in protest.
[src:raygui/opengl] Most complaints revolved around the lack of communication by Khronos to the development community and multiple features being discarded that were viewed favorably by many.
[src:raygui/opengl] Other frustrations included the requirement of DirectX 10 level hardware to use OpenGL 3.0 and the absence of geometry shaders and instanced rendering as core features.
[src:raygui/opengl] Other sources reported that the community reaction was not quite as severe as originally presented, with many vendors showing support for the update.
[src:raygui/opengl] OpenGL 3.0 introduced a deprecation mechanism to simplify future revisions of the API.
[src:raygui/opengl] Certain features, marked as deprecated, could be completely disabled by requesting a *forward-compatible context* from the windowing system.
[src:raygui/opengl] OpenGL 3.0 features could still be accessed alongside these deprecated features, however, by requesting a *full context*.
[src:raygui/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 8 Series and newer, ATI Radeon HD 2000 series and newer, Intel HD Graphics in Intel Sandy Bridge processors and newer.
[src:raygui/opengl] OpenGL 3.1 fully removed all of the features which were deprecated in version 3.0, with the exception of wide lines.
[src:raygui/opengl] From this version onwards, it's not possible to access new features using a *full context*, or to access deprecated features using a *forward-compatible context*.
[src:raygui/opengl] An exception to the former rule is made if the implementation supports the ARB_compatibility extension, but this is not guaranteed.
[src:raygui/opengl] Hardware support: Mesa supports ARM Panfrost with Version 21.0.
[src:raygui/opengl] OpenGL 3.2 further built on the deprecation mechanisms introduced by OpenGL 3.0, by dividing the specification into a *core profile* and *compatibility profile*.
[src:raygui/opengl] Compatibility contexts include the previously removed fixed-function APIs, equivalent to the ARB_compatibility extension released alongside OpenGL 3.1, while core contexts do not.
[src:raygui/opengl] OpenGL 3.2 also included an upgrade to GLSL version 1.50.
[src:raygui/opengl] OpenGL 3.3 includes minor additions, with the goal of retaining as much functionality as possible from OpenGL 4.0, while keeping support for older hardware.
[src:raygui/opengl] Additions include new blending functions, Sampler Objects and new texture and vertex formats.
[src:raygui/opengl] Support is also added for GLSL version 3.30, major and minor versions now match with OpenGL.
[src:raygui/opengl] OpenGL 4.0 was released alongside version 3.3.
[src:raygui/opengl] It was designed for hardware able to support Direct3D 11.
[src:raygui/opengl] As in OpenGL 3.0, this version of OpenGL contains a high number of fairly inconsequential extensions, designed to thoroughly expose the abilities of Direct3D 11-class hardware, such as tessellation.
[src:raygui/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Ivy Bridge processors and newer.
[src:raygui/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Haswell processors and newer (Linux Mesa: Ivy Bridge and newer).
[src:raygui/opengl] Additionally, this is the last core profile supported by Apple macOS.
[src:raygui/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), and Intel HD Graphics in Intel Haswell processors and newer.
[src:raygui/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Haswell processors and newer.
[src:raygui/opengl] (Linux Mesa: Ivy Bridge without stencil texturing, Haswell and newer), Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer.
[src:raygui/opengl] VIRGL Emulation for virtual machines supports 4.3+ with Mesa 20.
[src:raygui/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Broadwell processors and newer (Linux Mesa: Haswell and newer), Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, Tegra K1.
[src:raygui/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Broadwell processors and newer (Linux Mesa: Haswell and newer), Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, Tegra K1, and Tegra X1.
[src:raygui/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 7000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel Skylake and newer, Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer.
[src:raygui/opengl] Apple deprecated OpenGL in iOS 12 and macOS 10.14 Mojave in favor of Metal, but it is still available as of macOS 15 Sequoia (including on Apple silicon devices).
[src:raygui/opengl] The latest version supported for OpenGL is 4.1 from 2011.
[src:raygui/opengl] A proprietary library from Molten – authors of MoltenVK – called MoltenGL, can translate OpenGL calls to Metal.
[src:raygui/opengl] There are several projects that attempt to implement OpenGL on top of Vulkan.
[src:raygui/opengl] The Vulkan backend for Google's ANGLE achieved OpenGL ES 3.1 conformance in July 2020.
[src:raygui/opengl] The Mesa3D project also includes such a driver, called *Zink*.
[src:raygui/opengl] Microsoft's Windows 11 on Arm added support for OpenGL 3.3 via GLon12, an open source OpenGL implementation on top DirectX 12 via Mesa Gallium.
[src:raygui/opengl] Vulkan, formerly named the "Next Generation OpenGL Initiative" (glNext), is a ground-up redesign effort to unify OpenGL and OpenGL ES into one common API that will not be backwards compatible with existing OpenGL versions.
[src:raygui/opengl] The initial version of Vulkan API was released on February 16, 2016.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The term "Ray Casting" was introduced by Scott Roth while at the General Motors Research Labs from 1978–1980.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] His paper, "Ray Casting for Modeling Solids", describes modeled solid objects by combining primitive solids, such as blocks and cylinders, using the set operators union (+), intersection (&), and difference (−).
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The general idea of using these binary operators for solid modeling is largely due to Voelcker and Requicha's geometric modelling group at the University of Rochester.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Before ray casting (and ray tracing), computer graphics algorithms projected surfaces or edges (e.g., lines) from the 3D world to the image plane where visibility logic had to be applied.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The world-to-image plane projection is a 3D homogeneous coordinate system transformation, also known as 3D projection, affine transformation, or projective transform (homography).
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Rendering an image this way is difficult to achieve with hidden surface/edge removal.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Plus, silhouettes of curved surfaces have to be explicitly solved for whereas it is an implicit by-product of ray casting, so there is no need to explicitly solve for it whenever the view changes.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Ray casting greatly simplified image rendering of 3D objects and scenes because a line transforms to a line.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] So, instead of projecting curved edges and surfaces in the 3D scene to the 2D image plane, transformed lines (rays) are intersected with the objects in the scene.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] A homogeneous coordinate transformation is represented by a 4×4 matrix.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The mathematical technique is common to computer graphics and geometric modeling.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] A transform includes rotations around the three axes, independent scaling along the axes, translations in 3D, and even skewing.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Transforms are easily concatenated via matrix arithmetic.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] For use with a 4×4 matrix, a point is represented by [*X*, *Y*, *Z*, 1], and a direction vector is represented by [*Dx*, *Dy*, *Dz*, 0].
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Ray casting is the most basic of many computer graphics rendering algorithms that use the geometric algorithm of ray tracing.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Ray tracing-based rendering algorithms operate in image order to render three-dimensional scenes to two-dimensional images.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Geometric rays are traced from the eye of the observer to sample the light (radiance) travelling toward the observer from the ray direction.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The speed and simplicity of ray casting comes from computing the color of the light without recursively tracing additional rays that sample the radiance incident on the point that the ray hit.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] This eliminates the possibility of accurately rendering reflections, refractions, or the natural falloff of shadows; however all of these elements can be faked to a degree, by creative use of texture maps or other methods.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The high speed of calculation made ray casting a handy rendering method in early real-time 3D video games.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The idea behind ray casting is to trace rays from the eye, one per pixel, and find the closest object blocking the path of that ray—think of an image as a screen-door, with each square in the screen being a pixel.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] This is then the object the eye sees through that pixel.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Using the material properties and the effect of the lights in the scene, this algorithm can determine the shading of this object.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The simplifying assumption is made that if a surface faces a light, the light will reach that surface and not be blocked or in shadow.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The shading of the surface is computed using traditional 3D computer graphics shading models.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] One important advantage ray casting offered over older scanline algorithms was its ability to easily deal with non-planar surfaces and solids, such as cones and spheres.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] If a mathematical surface can be intersected by a ray, it can be rendered using ray casting.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Elaborate objects can be created by using solid modelling techniques and easily rendered.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Light rays and the camera geometry form the basis for all geometric reasoning here.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] This figure shows a pinhole camera model for perspective effect in image processing and a parallel camera model for mass analysis.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The simple pinhole camera model consists of a focal point (or eye point) and a square pixel array (or screen).
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Straight light rays pass through the pixel array to connect the focal point with the scene, one ray per pixel.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] To shade pictures, the rays’ intensities are measured and stored as pixels.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The reflecting surface responsible for a pixel’s value intersects the pixel’s ray.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] When the focal length, distance between focal point and screen, is infinite, then the view is called “parallel” because all light rays are parallel to each other, perpendicular to the screen.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Although the perspective view is natural for making pictures, some applications need rays that can be uniformly distributed in space.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] For modeling convenience, a typical standard coordinate system for the camera has the screen in the X–Y plane, the scene in the +Z half space, and the focal point on the −Z axis.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] A *ray* is simply a straight line in the 3D space of the camera model.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] It is best defined in parameterized form as a point vector (*X*0, *Y*0, *Z*0) and a direction vector (*Dx*, *Dy*, *Dz*).
[src:raygui/ray-casting] In this form, points on the line are ordered and accessed via a single parameter t.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] If the vector is normalized, then the parameter t is distance along the line.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Where n is the number of ray-surface intersections.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The ordered list of ray parameters, *t* [*i*], denote the enter–exit points.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The ray enters a solid at point *t* [1], exits at *t* [2], enters a solid at *t* [3], etc.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Point *t* [1] is closest to the camera and *t* [*n*] is furthest.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] In association with the ray parameters, the surface pointers contain a unique address for the intersected surface’s information.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The surface can have various properties such as color, specularity, transparency with/without refraction, translucency, etc.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The solid associated with the surface may have its own physical properties such as density.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] This could be useful, for instance, when an object consists of an assembly of different materials and the overall center of mass and moments of inertia are of interest.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Three algorithms using ray casting are to make line drawings, to make shaded pictures, and to compute volumes and other physical properties.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Each algorithm, given a camera model, casts one ray per pixel in the screen.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] For computing volume, the resolution of the pixel screen to use depends on the desired accuracy of the solution.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] For line drawings and picture shading, the resolution determines the quality of the image.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] To draw the visible edges of a solid, generate one ray per pixel moving top-down, left-right in the screen.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Evaluate each ray in order to identify the visible surface *S* [1], the first surface pointer in the sorted list of ray-surface intersections.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] If the visible surface at pixel location (*X*, *Y* ) is different than the visible surface at pixel (*X* − 1, *Y* ), then display a vertical line one pixel long centered at (*X* − ½, *Y* ).
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Similarly, if the visible surface at (*X*, *Y* ) is different than the visible surface at pixel (*X*, *Y* − 1), then display a horizontal line one pixel long centered at (*X*, *Y* − ½).
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The resulting drawing will consist of horizontal and vertical edges only, looking jagged in coarse resolutions.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Roth’s ray casting system generated the images of solid objects on the right.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Box enclosures, dynamic bounding, and coherence were used for optimization.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] For each picture, the screen was sampled with a density of about 100×100 (i.e., 10,000) rays and new edges were located via binary searches.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Then all edges were followed by casting additional rays at one pixel increments on the two sides of the edges.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Each picture was drawn on a Tektronix tube at 780×780 resolution.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] To make a shaded picture, again cast one ray per pixel in the screen.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] This time, however, use the visible surface pointer S[1] at each pixel to access the description of the surface.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] From this, compute the surface normal at the visible point *t* [1].
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The pixel’s value, the displayable light intensity, is proportional to the cosine of the angle formed by the surface normal and the light-source-to-surface vector.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Processing all pixels this way produces a raster-type picture of the scene.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The volume (and similar properties) of a solid bounded by curved surfaces is easily computed by the “approximating sums” integration method, by approximating the solid with a set of rectangular parallelepipeds.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] This is accomplished by taking an “in-depth” picture of the solid in a parallel view.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Casting rays through the screen into the solid partitions the solid into volume elements.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Two dimensions of the parallelepipeds are constant, defined by the 2D spacing of rays in the screen.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The third dimension is variable, defined by the enter–exit point computed.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] where L is defined as the length of the direction vector.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Each ${\tfrac {t[i]\ -\ t[i-1]}{L}}$ is a length of a ray segment that is inside of the solid.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] This figure shows the parallelepipeds for a modeled solid using ray casting.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] This is a use of parallel-projection camera model.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] This figure shows an example of the binary operators in a composition tree using “+” and “−” where a single ray is evaluated.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The ray casting procedure starts at the top of the solid composition tree, recursively descends to the bottom, classifies the ray with respect to the primitive solids, and then returns up the tree combining the classifications of the left and right subtrees.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] This figure illustrates the combining of the left and right classifications for all three binary operators.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Ray casting is a natural modeling tool for making shaded pictures.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The grayscale ray-casting system developed by Scott Roth and Daniel Bass at GM Research Labs produced pictures on a Ramtek color raster display around 1979.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] This figure shows a table scene with shadows from two point light sources.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Shading algorithms that implement all of the realistic effects are computationally expensive, but relatively simple.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] For example, the following figure shows the additional rays that could be cast for a single light source.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] For a single pixel in the image to be rendered, the algorithm casts a ray starting at the focal point and determines that it intersects a semi-transparent rectangle and a shiny circle.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] An additional ray must then be cast starting at that point in the direction symmetrically opposite the surface normal at the ray-surface intersection point in order to determine what is visible in the mirrored reflection.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] That ray intersects the triangle which is opaque.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Finally, each ray-surface intersection point is tested to determine if it is in shadow.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The “Shadow feeler” ray is cast from the ray-surface intersection point to the light source to determine if any other surface blocks that pathway.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The secondary ray is then processed as a specular ray.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] For the refraction formula and pictorial examples, see Whitted’s paper.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Ray casting qualifies as a brute force method for solving problems.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The minimal algorithm is simple, particularly in consideration of its many applications and ease of use, but applications typically cast many rays.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Millions of rays may be cast to render a single frame of an animated film.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Computer processing time increases with the resolution of the screen and the number of primitive solids/surfaces in the composition.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] By using minimum bounding boxes around the solids in the composition tree, the exhaustive search for a ray-solid intersection resembles an efficient binary search.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The brute force algorithm does an exhaustive search because it always visits all the nodes in the tree—transforming the ray into primitives’ local coordinate systems, testing for ray-surface intersections, and combining the classifications—even when the ray clearly misses the solid.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] In order to detect a “clear miss”, a faster algorithm uses the binary composition tree as a hierarchical representation of the space that the solid composition occupies.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] But all position, shape, and size information is stored at the leaves of the tree where primitive solids reside.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The top and intermediate nodes in the tree only specify combine operators.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Characterizing with enclosures the space that all solids fill gives all nodes in the tree an abstract summary of position and size information.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Then, the quick “ray intersects enclosure” tests guide the search in the hierarchy.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] When the test fails at an intermediate node in the tree, the ray is guaranteed to classify as out of the composite, so recursing down its subtrees to further investigate is unnecessary.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Accurately assessing the cost savings for using enclosures is difficult because it depends on the spatial distribution of the primitives (the complexity distribution) and on the organization of the composition tree.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The following are miscellaneous performance improvements made in Roth’s paper on ray casting, but there have been considerable improvements subsequently made by others.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] If the operator at a composite node in the tree is − or & and the ray classifies as out of the composite’s left sub-solid, then the ray will classify as out of the composite regardless of the ray’s classification with respect to the right sub-solid.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] So, classifying the ray with respect to the right sub-solid is unnecessary and should be avoided for efficiency.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] By initially combining the screen-to-scene transform with the primitive’s scene-to-local transform and storing the resulting screen-to-local transforms in the primitive’s data structures, one ray transform per ray-surface intersection is eliminated.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Given a deep composition tree, recursion can be expensive in combination with allocating and freeing up memory.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Recursion can be simulated using static arrays as stacks.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] If only the visible edges of the solid are to be displayed, the ray casting algorithm can dynamically bound the ray to cut off the search.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] That is, after finding that a ray intersects a sub-solid, the algorithm can use the intersection point closest to the screen to tighten the depth bound for the “ray intersections box” test.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] This only works for the + part of the tree, starting at the top.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] With – and &, nearby “in” parts of the ray may later become “out”.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The principle of coherence is that the surfaces visible at two neighboring pixels are more likely to be the same than different.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Developers of computer graphics and vision systems have applied this empirical truth for efficiency and performance.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] For line drawings, the image area containing edges is normally much less than the total image area, so ray casting should be concentrated around the edges and not in the open regions.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] This can be effectively implemented by sparsely sampling the screen with rays and then locating, when neighboring rays identify different visible surfaces, the edges via binary searches.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The jagged edges caused by aliasing is an undesirable effect of point sampling techniques and is a classic problem with raster display algorithms.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Linear or smoothly curved edges will appear jagged and are particularly objectionable in animations because movement of the image makes the edges appear fuzzy or look like little moving escalators.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Also, details in the scene smaller than the spacing between rays may be lost.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The jagged edges in a line drawing can be smoothed by edge following.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The purpose of such an algorithm is to minimize the number of lines needed to draw the picture within one pixel accuracy.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The line drawings above were drawn this way.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] To smooth the jagged edges in a shaded picture with subpixel accuracy, additional rays should be cast for information about the edges.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] (See Supersampling for a general approach.) Edges are formed by the intersection of surfaces or by the profile of a curved surface.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Applying "Coherence" as described above via binary search, if the visible surface at pixel (*X*, *Y* ) is different than the visible surface at pixel (*X* + 1, *Y* ), then a ray could be generated midway between them at (*X* + ½, *Y* ) and the visible surface there identified.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The distance between sample points could be further subdivided, but the search need not be deep.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The primary search depth to smooth jagged edges is a function of the intensity gradient across the edge.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] For the history of ray casting, see Ray tracing (graphics) as both are essentially the same technique under different names.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Scott Roth had invented the term "ray casting" before having heard of "ray tracing".
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Additionally, Scott Roth's development of ray casting at GM Research Labs occurred concurrently with Turner Whitted's ray tracing work at Bell Labs.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] In early first person games, raycasting was used to efficiently render a 3D world from a 2D playing field using a simple one-dimensional scan over the horizontal width of the screen.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Early first-person shooters used 2D ray casting as a technique to create a 3D effect from a 2D world.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] While the world appears 3D, the player cannot look up or down or only in limited angles with shearing distortion.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] This style of rendering eliminates the need to fire a ray for each pixel in the frame as is the case with modern engines; once the hit point is found the projection distortion is applied to the surface texture and an entire vertical column is copied from the result into the frame.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] This style of rendering also imposes limitations on the type of rendering which can be performed, for example **depth sorting** but depth buffering may not.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] That is polygons must be full in front of or behind one another, they may not partially overlap or intersect.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The video game *Wolfenstein 3D* was built from a square based grid of uniform height walls meeting solid-colored floors and ceilings.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] In order to draw the world, a single ray was traced for every column of screen pixels and a vertical slice of wall texture was selected and scaled according to where in the world the ray hits a wall and how far it travels before doing so.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The purpose of the grid based levels was twofold — ray-wall collisions can be found more quickly since the potential hits become more predictable and memory overhead is reduced.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] However, encoding wide-open areas takes extra space.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The Raven Software game *ShadowCaster* uses an improved Wolfenstein-based engine with added floors and ceilings texturing and variable wall heights.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The Voxel Space engine developed by NovaLogic for the *Comanche* games traced a ray through each column of screen pixels and tested each ray against points in a heightmap.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Then it transformed each element of the heightmap into a column of pixels, determined which are visible (that is, have not been occluded by pixels that have been drawn in front), and drew them with the corresponding color from the texture map.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] Later DOS games like *id Software's DOOM* kept many of the raycasting 2.5D restrictions for speed but went on to switch to alternative rendering techniques (like BSP), making them no longer raycasting engines.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] The problem has been investigated for various settings: space dimension, types of objects, restrictions on query rays, etc.
[src:raygui/ray-casting] One technique is to use a sparse voxel octree.
[src:raygui/raylib] The library is designed to be suited for prototyping, tooling, graphical applications, embedded systems, and education.
[src:raygui/raylib] The source code is written in the C programming language (specifically using C99), which is distributed under a zlib/libpng OSI certified open-source license.
[src:raygui/raylib] It supports compilation to several target platforms, including Windows, Linux, macOS, FreeBSD, Android, Raspberry Pi and HTML5.
[src:raygui/raylib] raylib has been ported to more than 70 programming languages in the form of bindings, but many of these ports are not stable.
[src:raygui/raylib] raylib development began in August 2013 when Ramon Santamaria created the library to support a game development course aimed at students with artistic backgrounds and no prior coding experience.
[src:raygui/raylib] Student feedback throughout the course shaped its early development, and by mid-2014 the library was being showcased at game development events in Barcelona.
[src:raygui/raylib] raylib 1.0 was released in November 2013, offering basic functionality for window management, 2D/3D rendering, texture and font loading, and audio playback.
[src:raygui/raylib] Eight minor releases over the following five years added Android, WebAssembly, and Raspberry Pi support, multiple OpenGL backends, VR support, shaders, a physics module, and an expanding examples library.
[src:raygui/raylib] raylib 2.0 was released in July 2018, coinciding with Santamaria leaving his professorship to focus on raylib full-time.
[src:raygui/raylib] All external dependencies were removed, OpenAL was replaced by the miniaudio library, and continuous integration support was introduced.
[src:raygui/raylib] A subsequent minor release, raylib 2.5, added Unicode text rendering, skeletal animation with glTF support, and a redesigned gamepad system.
[src:raygui/raylib] raylib 3.0 was released in April 2020, refactoring the codebase to improve portability and language binding support.
[src:raygui/raylib] Global state was consolidated into context structures, and all file I/O was centralized to allow custom virtual filesystem integration.
[src:raygui/raylib] Bindings for over 40 programming languages were available by this point.
[src:raygui/raylib] A minor update, raylib 3.5, followed in December 2020, adding Raspberry Pi 4 native mode and improved software rendering aimed at embedded devices.
[src:raygui/raylib] raylib 4.0 was released in November 2021, focusing on API consistency through broad renaming and documentation improvements.
[src:raygui/raylib] It introduced an experimental input recording and replay system, optional user-controlled game-loop timing, and OpenGL 4.3 support, with rlgl and raymath promoted to usable standalone libraries.
[src:raygui/raylib] raylib 5.0 was released in November 2023 to mark the library's 10th anniversary.
[src:raygui/raylib] Its most significant change was splitting the core platform module into separate, swappable backends, making new platform support far more approachable, with SDL2 added as an alternative desktop backend alongside an unofficial Nintendo Switch backend.
[src:raygui/raylib] Spline drawing, a new pseudo-random number generator, and a redesigned automation events system were also introduced.
[src:raygui/raylib] A minor release, raylib 5.5, followed in November 2024, adding RGFW and SDL3 as additional platform backends, GPU skinning support for 3D model animations.
[src:raygui/raylib] A software renderer backend was introduced, allowing raylib to run entirely on CPU without a GPU.
[src:raygui/raylib] New platform backends were added for Win32 and Emscripten without third-party library dependencies, alongside a headless memory framebuffer mode.
[src:raygui/raylib] Fullscreen and High-DPI scaling were completely redesigned, and the skeletal animation system was rebuilt to support blending between animations.
[src:raygui/raylib] The examples collection grew past 215 entries, and a dedicated examples management tool was introduced to streamline contributions.
[src:raygui/raylib] This is a simple example that creates a window with text, given on the GitHub page of Raylib.
[src:raygui/raylib] As of April 2026, GitHub lists around 2500 projects matching the `raylib` topic.
[src:raygui/raylib] raylib consists of several modules that are exposed to the programmer through the API.
[src:raygui/raylib] raylib has bindings for more than 70 different programming languages, created by various language communities.
[src:raygui/raylib] Computer programming languages that are updated to the latest version include: C#, Crystal, D (Dlang), Fortran, Go, Jai, Java, Lua, Nim, Python, Rust, V (Vlang), and Zig.
[src:raygui/raylib] There is also a C++ wrapper for users of C++ who prefer a less C-like, more C++-idiomatic usage, and also can be imported as a C++ module.
[src:raygui/raylib] A list of bindings is available in the BINDINGS.md file in the raylib GitHub repository.
